A Go-based payment workflow has been running in production for 8 months. The team needs to replace `ActivityA` with `ActivityC`. They deploy the following patched code:

```go
v := workflow.GetVersion(ctx, "Step1", workflow.DefaultVersion, 1)
if v == workflow.DefaultVersion {
    err = workflow.ExecuteActivity(ctx, ActivityA, data).Get(ctx, &result1)
} else {
    err = workflow.ExecuteActivity(ctx, ActivityC, data).Get(ctx, &result1)
}
```

Three months later, all pre-patch workflows have completed. The team raises `minSupported` to `1` and removes the `DefaultVersion` branch. One week after that, they discover that some workflows are now failing with nondeterminism errors on replay. What is the most likely cause?

A team has a Go workflow that uses `workflow.GetVersion` for two independent changes at different points in the code:

```go
// Point 1 in the workflow
v1 := workflow.GetVersion(ctx, "Step1", workflow.DefaultVersion, 1)
if v1 == workflow.DefaultVersion {
    err = workflow.ExecuteActivity(ctx, ActivityA, data).Get(ctx, &r1)
} else {
    err = workflow.ExecuteActivity(ctx, ActivityC, data).Get(ctx, &r1)
}

// Point 2 in the workflow  
v2 := workflow.GetVersion(ctx, "Step2", workflow.DefaultVersion, 1)
if v2 == workflow.DefaultVersion {
    err = workflow.ExecuteActivity(ctx, ActivityB, r1).Get(ctx, &r2)
} else {
    err = workflow.ExecuteActivity(ctx, ActivityD, r1).Get(ctx, &r2)
}
```

Old workers (pre-patch, no `GetVersion` calls) are still running some open executions. A new worker begins replaying an old execution that ran `ActivityA` and then `ActivityB` and has now advanced past Point 1 but not yet reached Point 2. When the new worker resumes this execution at Point 2, what does `workflow.GetVersion(ctx, "Step2", ...)` return for that specific execution?
